<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1437,1266,1977]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
1859. 
<emphasis box="[223,467,1267,1293]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName box="[223,463,1267,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Stenopelmatus minor</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Revue et Magasin de Zoologie 2(11): 210. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[970,1227,1267,1293]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<typeStatus box="[970,1088,1267,1293]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Lectotype</typeStatus>
adult male
</emphasis>
, with hooks, 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">here selected</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[262,344,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 84" captionStartId="57.[151,250,657,681]" captionTargetBox="[220,1306,193,631]" captionTargetId="figure-19@57.[220,1368,179,631]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 84. Lectotype adult male S. minor (photo J. Hollier)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4472142" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4472142/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[344,353,1302,1328]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">)</emphasis>
: (1) Cordova [Córdoba, state of 
<collectingRegion box="[730,833,1303,1329]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[845,934,1302,1329]" name="Mexico" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Mexico</collectingCountry>
] (2) 
<taxonomicName authority="Sss" authorityName="Sss" box="[990,1142,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">St. minor Sss</taxonomicName>
(3) 91 (4) 
<taxonomicName authority="Sauss" authorityName="Sauss" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Stenopelmatus minor Sauss</taxonomicName>
(5) red paper 
<typeStatus box="[445,555,1339,1365]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Allotypus</typeStatus>
<taxonomicName authority="Sauss. THH." authorityName="Sauss. THH." box="[562,949,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Stenopelmatus minor Sauss. THH.</taxonomicName>
Measurements in mm (courtesy J. Hollier): Body length 19.5, hind femur length 8.0, hind femur width 2.2. Left hind tibia (
<figureCitation box="[1061,1144,1374,1401]" captionStart="FIGURE 85" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1310,1334]" captionTargetBox="[514,1067,728,1269]" captionTargetId="figure-34@57.[512,1075,706,1287]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 85. Hind tibia lectotype adult male S. minor showing 3 inner (left photo) and 1 outer (right photo) spines. He is missing his right rear leg. Given that the allotype female from the same locality has 3 outer tibial spines, we suspect that the lectotype male suffered some damage to his left tibia when an earlier instar." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4472144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4472144/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
) with 1 outer and 3 inner spines. Face 
<figureCitation box="[292,374,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 86" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1977,2001]" captionTargetBox="[427,1159,1434,1950]" captionTargetId="figure-99@57.[426,1162,1431,1953]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 86. Lectotype adult male (left photo) showing lateral wall of furrow (arrow). Allotopotype adult female (right photo) without furrow." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4472146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4472146/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fig. 86</figureCitation>
. Deposited in MHNG Geneva along with allotopotype.Allotopotype adult female (
<figureCitation box="[1292,1372,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURE 87" captionStartId="58.[151,250,701,725]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,195,673]" captionTargetId="figure-21@58.[152,1436,181,677]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 87. Allotopotype adult female S. minor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4472148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4472148/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fig. 87</figureCitation>
) with same label data except (3) 92. Measurements in mm: Body length 15.6, hind femur length 7.8, hind femur width 2.6. Hind tibia with 3 outer and 4 inner spines (
<figureCitation box="[679,763,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 88" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1349,1373]" captionTargetBox="[244,1342,790,1324]" captionTargetId="figure-33@58.[239,1348,785,1324]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 88. Left hind leg tibia of allotopotype adult female S. minor showing 4 inner (left photo) and 3 outer (right photo) spines." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4472150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4472150/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fig. 88</figureCitation>
). Face 
<figureCitation box="[843,925,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 86" captionStartId="57.[151,250,1977,2001]" captionTargetBox="[427,1159,1434,1950]" captionTargetId="figure-99@57.[426,1162,1431,1953]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 86. Lectotype adult male (left photo) showing lateral wall of furrow (arrow). Allotopotype adult female (right photo) without furrow." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4472146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4472146/files/figure.png" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fig. 86</figureCitation>
. The female is in better condition because the male is missing both the middle and hind right legs, which is why 
<bibRefCitation author="Hubbell, T. H." box="[894,1066,1519,1546]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" refId="ref49981" refString="Hubbell, T. H. (1960) Notes on Orthoptera in European Museums. Unpublished notes deposited at University of Michigan, Museum of Zoology, Ann Arbor, Michigan, 28 pp." type="book" year="1960">Hubbell (1960)</bibRefCitation>
preferred that the female be designated the 
<typeStatus box="[282,385,1555,1581]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">lectotype</typeStatus>
and attached an “ 
<typeStatus box="[582,698,1555,1581]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Allotypus</typeStatus>
” label to the male. Nevertheless, when given a choice between an adult male vs adult female as 
<typeStatus box="[481,587,1591,1617]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">lectotype</typeStatus>
, we choose the former because the presence of mature hooks will absolutely confirm adult status. Additionally, 
<emphasis box="[538,554,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">if</emphasis>
there are distinctive characters in the articulated ringlet of 6 calcars, then those characters may be more prominent in males. Both specimens are mentioned in the original description. In any case, we declare a 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[298,632,1698,1725]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">New status: nomen dubium,</emphasis>
in the absence of DNA and drum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1437,1266,1977]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis box="[199,425,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Derivation of name.</emphasis>
We assume “minor” in reference to its small size. In fact, as 
<tableCitation box="[1109,1192,1735,1761]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="15.[151,170,493,520]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="TABLE 1. Summary of adult measurements (mm) in Stenopelmatus taxa with multiple adult specimens." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF7225BE8A7EFB439B8420DC1BEFFDCF" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" tableUuid="DF7225BE8A7EFB439B8420DC1BEFFDCF">Table 1</tableCitation>
demonstrates (p. 16), there are several smaller 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1838" box="[431,594,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[431,594,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Stenopelmatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa in 
<collectingCountry box="[684,773,1771,1797]" name="Mexico" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1437,1266,1977]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis box="[199,330,1807,1832]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Discussion.</emphasis>
We were tempted to let this name stand since it would have page priority over other small black species 
<taxonomicName box="[242,323,1843,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nieti">
<emphasis box="[242,323,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">S. nieti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[382,493,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName box="[382,489,1843,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">S. histrio</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
if all three should be synonyms. Nevertheless, the diversity of small, black 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1838" class="Insecta" family="Stenopelmatidae" genus="Stenopelmatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Stenopelmatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in 
<collectingCountry box="[311,399,1879,1905]" name="Mexico" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, while unknown, easily exceeds 6 (
<tableCitation box="[800,885,1879,1905]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="15.[151,170,493,520]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="TABLE 1. Summary of adult measurements (mm) in Stenopelmatus taxa with multiple adult specimens." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF7225BE8A7EFB439B8420DC1BEFFDCF" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" tableUuid="DF7225BE8A7EFB439B8420DC1BEFFDCF">Table 1</tableCitation>
). This situation will be unresolvable without the behavioral information of hop vs no hop, and drumming pattern. If karyotype and DNA information can be included in future systematics, then even better.
</paragraph>
